\title{Semgrep Rule Creator}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Creates custom Semgrep rules for detecting security vulnerabilities, bug patterns, and code patterns. Use when writing Semgrep rules or building custom static analysis detections.}

\subtree{
\title{Semgrep Rule Creator}
\p{Create production-quality Semgrep rules with proper testing and validation.}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\p{\strong{Ideal scenarios:}}

\ul{
\li{Writing Semgrep rules for specific bug patterns}
\li{Writing rules to detect security vulnerabilities in your codebase}
\li{Writing taint mode rules for data flow vulnerabilities}
\li{Writing rules to enforce coding standards}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{When NOT to Use}
\p{Do NOT use this skill for:}

\ul{
\li{Running existing Semgrep rulesets}
\li{General static analysis without custom rules (use \code{\startverb static-analysis\stopverb} skill)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Rationalizations to Reject}
\p{When writing Semgrep rules, reject these common shortcuts:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{"The pattern looks complete"} → Still run \code{\startverb semgrep --test --config <rule-id>.yaml <rule-id>.<ext>\stopverb} to verify. Untested rules have hidden false positives/negatives.}
\li{\strong{"It matches the vulnerable case"} → Matching vulnerabilities is half the job. Verify safe cases don't match (false positives break trust).}
\li{\strong{"Taint mode is overkill for this"} → If data flows from user input to a dangerous sink, taint mode gives better precision than pattern matching.}
\li{\strong{"One test is enough"} → Include edge cases: different coding styles, sanitized inputs, safe alternatives, and boundary conditions.}
\li{\strong{"I'll optimize the patterns first"} → Write correct patterns first, optimize after all tests pass. Premature optimization causes regressions.}
\li{\strong{"The AST dump is too complex"} → The AST reveals exactly how Semgrep sees code. Skipping it leads to patterns that miss syntactic variations.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Anti-Patterns}
\p{\strong{Too broad} - matches everything, useless for detection:}

\pre{\startverb
# BAD: Matches any function call
pattern: $FUNC(...)

# GOOD: Specific dangerous function
pattern: eval(...)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Missing safe cases in tests} - leads to undetected false positives:}

\pre{\startverb
# BAD: Only tests vulnerable case
# ruleid: my-rule
dangerous(user_input)

# GOOD: Include safe cases to verify no false positives
# ruleid: my-rule
dangerous(user_input)

# ok: my-rule
dangerous(sanitize(user_input))

# ok: my-rule
dangerous("hardcoded_safe_value")
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Overly specific patterns} - misses variations:}

\pre{\startverb
# BAD: Only matches exact format
pattern: os.system("rm " + $VAR)

# GOOD: Matches all os.system calls with taint tracking
mode: taint
pattern-sources:
  - pattern: input(...)
pattern-sinks:
  - pattern: os.system(...)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Strictness Level}
\p{This workflow is \strong{strict} - do not skip steps:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Read documentation first}: See [Documentation](#documentation) before writing Semgrep rules}
\li{\strong{Test-first is mandatory}: Never write a rule without tests}
\li{\startverb **100% test pass is required**: "Most tests pass" is not acceptable\stopverb}
\li{\strong{Optimization comes last}: Only simplify patterns after all tests pass}
\li{\strong{Avoid generic patterns}: Rules must be specific, not match broad patterns}
\li{\strong{Prioritize taint mode}: For data flow vulnerabilities}
\li{\strong{One YAML file - one Semgrep rule}: Each YAML file must contain only one Semgrep rule; don't combine multiple rules in a single file}
\li{\strong{No generic rules}: When targeting a specific language for Semgrep rules - avoid generic pattern matching (\code{\startverb languages: generic\stopverb})}
\li{\strong{Forbidden \code{\startverb todook\stopverb} and \code{\startverb todoruleid\stopverb} test annotations}: \code{\startverb todoruleid: <rule-id>\stopverb} and \code{\startverb todook: <rule-id>\stopverb} annotations in tests files for future rule improvements are forbidden}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{This skill guides creation of Semgrep rules that detect security vulnerabilities and code patterns. Rules are created iteratively: analyze the problem, write tests first, analyze AST structure, write the rule, iterate until all tests pass, optimize the rule.}

\p{\strong{Approach selection:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Taint mode} (prioritize): Data flow issues where untrusted input reaches dangerous sinks}
\li{\strong{Pattern matching}: Simple syntactic patterns without data flow requirements}
}

\pre{\startverb
**Why prioritize taint mode?** Pattern matching finds syntax but misses context. A pattern `eval($X)` matches both `eval(user_input)` (vulnerable) and `eval("safe_literal")` (safe). Taint mode tracks data flow, so it only alerts when untrusted data actually reaches the sink—dramatically reducing false positives for injection vulnerabilities.
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Iterating between approaches:} It's okay to experiment. If you start with taint mode and it's not working well (e.g., taint doesn't propagate as expected, too many false positives/negatives), switch to pattern matching. Conversely, if pattern matching produces too many false positives on safe cases, try taint mode instead. The goal is a working rule—not rigid adherence to one approach.}

\p{\strong{Output structure} - exactly 2 files in a directory named after the rule-id:}

\pre{\startverb
<rule-id>/
├── <rule-id>.yaml     # Semgrep rule
└── <rule-id>.<ext>    # Test file with ruleid/ok annotations
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start}
\pre{\startverb
rules:
  - id: insecure-eval
    languages: [python]
    severity: HIGH
    message: User input passed to eval() allows code execution
    mode: taint
    pattern-sources:
      - pattern: request.args.get(...)
    pattern-sinks:
      - pattern: eval(...)
\stopverb}

\p{Test file (\code{\startverb insecure-eval.py\stopverb}):}

\pre{\startverb
# ruleid: insecure-eval
eval(request.args.get('code'))

# ok: insecure-eval
eval("print('safe')")
\stopverb}

\p{Run tests (from rule directory): \code{\startverb semgrep --test --config <rule-id>.yaml <rule-id>.<ext>\stopverb}}
}

